        "slug": "2023-intern-rishav-bikarwar-graviton-research-capital",
        "content": "\r\nRishav Bikarwar, studying in IIT Kanpur as a BTech student in CSE will do\r\nhis summer internship in Software profile at Graviton Research Capital. Here are some brief\r\ninsights of his.\r\n\r\n## Shortlisted Profiles & Companies:\r\n● Graviton Research Capital\r\n(Quant and Software)\r\n● AlphaGrep (Software)\r\n● QuantBox (Software)\r\n● Goldman Sachs (Software)\r\n\r\n## Insights on the Selection Process\r\nDuring the selection process, the initial resume shortlisting was based\r\non the CPI. The coding test that followed had a time limit of one hour\r\nand contained questions on topics such as tree traversal and Dynamic\r\nProgramming (DP). Additionally, the quantitative aptitude test included\r\nquestions on probability and discrete mathematics, with a focus on\r\nevaluating probability using recursion, expected values, and Bayes&#39;\r\ntheorem.\r\nThe first round of interview involved coding problems. They asked\r\nquestions from query data structure and tree operations. The second\r\nround of the interview focused on topics from CS220 (Computer\r\nOrganization) such as pipelining, memory management, and stack\r\nmanipulation. Overall, the selection process for the software profile was\r\nrigorous, and candidates were expected to have a solid understanding\r\nof both theoretical and practical concepts related to the field.\r\n\r\nSample Interview\r\n/Test Questions\r\n\r\n1. A variant of k-sum paths in a binary tree – find number of paths in a\r\nbinary tree that has sum k.\r\n2. Find kth largest number in a nxn matrix where each row and column\r\nis sorted in ascending order.\r\n3. Given an array where ith element represents max distance that can\r\nbe jumped from that position, find minimum number of jumps needed to\r\n\r\nreach last index.\r\n\r\n##  Preparation Resources\r\nFor Quant – 50 Challenging Problems, Brainstellar\r\nFor Coding – Interviewbit, Codeforces, CSES, Introduction to Algorithms by CLRS.\r\n\r\n## Advice for students (dos and don’ts)? \r\n- Practice coding regularly: Make sure to set aside time each day to work on coding problems,\r\nand don&#39;t be afraid to start small.\r\n- Don&#39;t get discouraged if you&#39;re unable to solve a problem right away. Instead, seek hints and\r\ncollaborate with others to work towards a solution. Joining a study group or participating in\r\nCodeforces / Codechef contests can also be a great way to learn from others and build your\r\nskills.\r\n- Attend any mock interviews or practice sessions organized by SPO to gain experience and\r\nget feedback on your performance.\r\n- For quant prep, try to solve probability questions on Bayes theorem and expectations. Solve\r\nthe problems from sources mentioned above at least two times.\r\n- Review your resume: Before applying for internships, make sure your resume is polished\r\nand professional. Get feedback from senior students or professors to ensure it stands out\r\nfrom the crowd.\r\n- Don&#39;t give up! Keep practicing, seeking help, and pushing yourself to improve.\r\n\r\n",
